    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3231003107" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3231003107" />
    <a title="Rachel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6069769-rachel"><img alt="Rachel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1561576559p2/6069769.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3231003107?book_show_action=true">Aug 25, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rachel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rachel" href="/user/show/6069769-rachel">Rachel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781635420166" href="/book/show/52256788-serenade-for-nadia">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6069769-rachel?shelf=jewishfiction2020">jewishfiction2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3231003107" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6458276987032312361">Ever since my visit in 1995, I have been interested in Turkey and its Jewish community. So I was very excited to read this newly translated book by one of Turkey&apos;s bestselling authors. Livaneli&apos;s novel centers around Maya, a single mother who works for Istanbul University in 2001 and is assigned to host a visiting American professor, Max Wagner. During his visit, Maya learns about the many German (both Jewish and Nazi connected) academics who were recruited by the Turkish government to modernize</span>
  <span id="freeText6458276987032312361" style="display:none">Ever since my visit in 1995, I have been interested in Turkey and its Jewish community. So I was very excited to read this newly translated book by one of Turkey's bestselling authors. Livaneli's novel centers around Maya, a single mother who works for Istanbul University in 2001 and is assigned to host a visiting American professor, Max Wagner. During his visit, Maya learns about the many German (both Jewish and Nazi connected) academics who were recruited by the Turkish government to modernize higher education as well as the Struma disaster which killed nearly 800 Jewish refugees trying to reach Palestine in 1942. She also learns about Max's wife Nadia. While the story was very interesting and I read the book quickly in 3 days, a few things bothered me. I'm not sure if it was the fault of the translator or because the author is a man, but I found his characterization of Maya very wooden and two-dimensional and her attitude towards her son, parenting, and motherhood not relatable or authentic. And I was totally shocked to read: "When does a girl stop growing up? . . . Life constantly changes her, and the principal agent of these changes is always a man." (p.385-386) I also felt like the author's research, while interesting and accessible, showed through too much. But, perhaps what bothered me most was that at several points in the story, Maya claims that she is Catholic, Muslim and Jewish. However, while we learn the tragic stories of her persecuted Armenian and Crimean grandparents, no one in her family was ever Jewish. She only feels Jewish after Max entrusted her with Nadia's story. I'm sorry, I don't buy it! And to me, this reeks of cultural appropriation. Would readers accept a character who claimed any other cultural/ethic/religious identity after simply learning a story about one individual? I doubt it. The story of the Struma needs to be told more but overall Serenade for Nadia was a disappointing read. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6458276987032312361" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

