<div id="review_3380861115" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3380861115" />
    <a title="Parsa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111732248-parsa"><img alt="Parsa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1584895024p2/111732248.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3380861115?book_show_action=true">Jul 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Parsa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Parsa" href="/user/show/111732248-parsa">Parsa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3380861115" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17070406847502116799">&quot;<b>Serenade für Nadia</b>&quot; is not so much a story as it is a <i>song</i>; a song of power and prejudice, of oppression and untold history. Livaneli does a fine job of retelling forgotten affairs and raveling the thin threads weaving human lives together through a series of emotional rollercoasters that gradually wear Maya, the protagonist <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[or is she? <a class='jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction'>(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, down to the point where she forfeits the walls around her obscure world and sees her pre-established ethical cues as subject to c</span>
  <span id="freeText17070406847502116799" style="display:none">"<b>Serenade für Nadia</b>" is not so much a story as it is a <i>song</i>; a song of power and prejudice, of oppression and untold history. Livaneli does a fine job of retelling forgotten affairs and raveling the thin threads weaving human lives together through a series of emotional rollercoasters that gradually wear Maya, the protagonist <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[or is she? <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, down to the point where she forfeits the walls around her obscure world and sees her pre-established ethical cues as subject to criticism, wisely disguised in a playful fling between progressive ideologies and unhinged anarchism set in modern-day Turkey, which, if nothing, is noticeably courageous of Livaneli. Maya entertains what she herself calls a <i>pseudo-philosophical</i> state of existential contemplation, narrated in a well-balanced fashion: slightly blunt so as not to exhaust the average reader, but also piercing enough to make one put down the book and simply <i>think</i>, from time to time.<br /><br />The emotional turmoil and the unceasing blows of grief and misery is told through the stories of <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[three women from three different timelines all somehow adding a portion of their experiences to their young prodigy, Maya, <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> which unfolds the horrific tales that have been unnaturally forgotten despite happening in the recent past.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">["Hayatı zaten o küçük Karadeniz kıyısında bitmişdi; şimdi gecikmiş olan töreni yapılacaktı." <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />These blows hit hard. You <b>will</b> cry reading this. Trust me.<br /><br />Simply put, have <s>a few</s> lots of tissue packs around while reading and be ready for a decent philosophical and historical journey with a juicy texture rich in detail (which would most likely not be appealing to all tastes) peculiar to Livaneli, from Maya's everyday life routine to the story behind a random painting in the English embassy, and the ideology behind the government's infrastructural design.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17070406847502116799" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

