<div id="review_3224651681" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3224651681" />
    <a title="Linda McCutcheon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28194465-linda-mccutcheon"><img alt="Linda McCutcheon" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3224651681?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Linda McCutcheon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Linda McCutcheon" href="/user/show/28194465-linda-mccutcheon">Linda McCutcheon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781635420166" href="/book/show/52256788-serenade-for-nadia">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3224651681" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13640972481016123632">Serenade For Nadia by Turkish writer Zulfu Livaneli, translated by Brendan Freely, is an historical fiction novel based on real life events between Turkey and Germany during World War II. <br/><br/>I am so grateful for this insightful, thoughtful, respectful novel that has the daunting task of retelling the 1942 tragedy of the Turkish ship Struma that was torpedoed by the Germans killing nearly 800 Jewish refugees on their way to Palestine.<br/><br/>The author opens in the year 2001 where we meet our narrator, Maya</span>
  <span id="freeText13640972481016123632" style="display:none">Serenade For Nadia by Turkish writer Zulfu Livaneli, translated by Brendan Freely, is an historical fiction novel based on real life events between Turkey and Germany during World War II. <br /><br />I am so grateful for this insightful, thoughtful, respectful novel that has the daunting task of retelling the 1942 tragedy of the Turkish ship Struma that was torpedoed by the Germans killing nearly 800 Jewish refugees on their way to Palestine.<br /><br />The author opens in the year 2001 where we meet our narrator, Maya, who befriends a visiting professor who has come back to Turkey after decades of self imposed exile from the country that was the last home of his deceased wife. Though a curmudgeon old man, Maya not only comes to respect him but to understand his heartbreaking pain from a war that destroyed too many lives.<br /><br />Though this is a somber topic, and a moment in history I never heard of before reading this book, the author eloquently has us fall in love with a young couple in 1938 not aware of the pending tragedy in their future. There are times that the realism of this event makes the story feel more like a non fiction book. However, at times it is necessary to understand that this disaster was not an accident. That the horror was inflicted against human beings by human beings on purpose. <br /><br />One of the positive results of this book is that by creating characters that we care about the tragedy becomes more personal and more real. I also think having the current timeline in 2001 is a brilliant way of reminding us that there is still too much hate in this world and this time over 3, 000 people lost their lives on 9/11.<br /><br />Despite the sadness this is a necessary story. We need history to be told so we learn and never let it happen again. Like Maya, we learn from the past to enjoy and be grateful for the life we are living thanks to those who have sacrificed so much for us to be here now.<br /><br />I received a free copy of this book for a fair and honest review. All opinions are my own.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13640972481016123632" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

