<div id="review_3395212780" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3395212780" />
    <a title="Doreen Fritz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1456404-doreen-fritz"><img alt="Doreen Fritz" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1275429997p2/1456404.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3395212780?book_show_action=true">Aug 05, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Doreen Fritz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Doreen Fritz" href="/user/show/1456404-doreen-fritz">Doreen Fritz</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781635420166" href="/book/show/52256788-serenade-for-nadia">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3395212780" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4050661883578031136">Written by a noted Turkish author, this novel tells the story of two characters: an elderly German professor who returns to Turkey to say a last farewell to his long-dead wife who was killed during WWII, and the woman who is assigned to escort him around town during his visit to Istanbul. This woman, Maya, a divorced woman raising her teenage son, works for the University. She later writes about the professor and tells the story of both him and his wife. There are a lot of red-herring rambles th</span>
  <span id="freeText4050661883578031136" style="display:none">Written by a noted Turkish author, this novel tells the story of two characters: an elderly German professor who returns to Turkey to say a last farewell to his long-dead wife who was killed during WWII, and the woman who is assigned to escort him around town during his visit to Istanbul. This woman, Maya, a divorced woman raising her teenage son, works for the University. She later writes about the professor and tells the story of both him and his wife. There are a lot of red-herring rambles that are not really part of the story - is Professor Max a spy? Why are people following him? Why are people giving Maya sideways looks - do they believe the taxi driver and his stories about her carrying on an affair with this 87-year-old man? We also hear about Maya's grandmothers, and there is a lot written about Turkey's economy, history, racism, genocides, and current political scene. Sometimes it's hard for the author to stay focused on what is really the story. There are leaps in time, and no clear organization of his writing --- but all in all the storylines are interesting, and I do enjoy learning about other cultures. This was just so poorly constructed that I was distracted, and didn't enjoy it as much as I might have. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4050661883578031136" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


