  <span id="freeText17617655654547148989" style="display:none">The readers should be very careful with female actors and their nationalities. The author explains a great part of the history of tahjir of Armenians from Anatolia and the modern politics of Turkey. While doing this, he chooses an Armenian woman who is hiding his nationality to be able to lead her life in Istanbul. However, Armenian tahjir is not the only human tragedy that happened to Armenians. The author chooses the holocaust to make comparisons and to justify with the cruelty of all governments saying 'no government is innocent. Every one of them kills'. It is very smart of the author how he chooses his characters (an Armenian, a Crimean Tatar, a Jew, and a Turk) and how he explains the course of history that changed their lives. It is enjoyable. </span>
