<div id="review_3376052931" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3376052931" />
    <a title="Josie Krieger" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/88142282-josie-krieger"><img alt="Josie Krieger" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1615654437p2/88142282.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3376052931?book_show_action=true">Jun 05, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Josie Krieger" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Josie Krieger" href="/user/show/88142282-josie-krieger">Josie Krieger</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/48928025-serenade-for-nadia">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3376052931" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer908886000406363065">I have never written a review for a book, but I felt compelled to do so because of my overall frustration with this piece. For such a historic injustice, I am disappointed in its retelling by Livaneli. I dare say I felt the character of Maya was quite shallow and I found it apparent that the story—revolving around the lives of multiple women—was written by a man. I saw other comments mention the sexism but my jaw dropped multiple times when I read certain lines. For example: &quot;Life constantly cha</span>
  <span id="freeText908886000406363065" style="display:none">I have never written a review for a book, but I felt compelled to do so because of my overall frustration with this piece. For such a historic injustice, I am disappointed in its retelling by Livaneli. I dare say I felt the character of Maya was quite shallow and I found it apparent that the story—revolving around the lives of multiple women—was written by a man. I saw other comments mention the sexism but my jaw dropped multiple times when I read certain lines. For example: "Life constantly changers her, and the principal agent of these changes is always a man" (pg. 385-386). In the middle of a story where a woman is uncovering the truth about her own family's secrets, systemic injustices, and inner conflict, the point to mention is that the biggest changes in her life has been... men??!? <br /><br />I would argue gives the men in her life far more credit than they deserve.<br /><br />Similarly, the fact that Maya's greatest conflict in the piece was a (SPOILER ALERT) sex scandal is beyond angering. Yes, the unequal focus on the sex lives of women in media is a real thing but, in a book about the Struma disaster and a woman uncovering her family's secret heritage... it's out of place and sexist. Women struggle with more than our sexual reputation. <br /><br />I give it two stars because the historical aspect of the book is fascinating and not often told, but overall I would not recommend reading this.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="908886000406363065" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


