<div id="review_3245197163" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3245197163" />
    <a title="Anita" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12192218-anita"><img alt="Anita" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3245197163?book_show_action=true">Sep 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anita" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anita" href="/user/show/12192218-anita">Anita</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/48928025-serenade-for-nadia">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3245197163" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15424814040368952885">I was glued to this book and felt tears at the end. Once again I learned about a whole new aspect of the scope of WWII Nazi Germany’s infiltration throughout the world. I had no idea that from 1939-1941, famous Jewish scientists fled from Nazi invaders to Turkey! Turkey had declared themselves neutral, however they were torn and coerced by both Nazi Germany and allied forces to side with them. Many scientists fled and were employed by the University of Istanbul. <br/>Maximilian Wagner, a famous scien</span>
  <span id="freeText15424814040368952885" style="display:none">I was glued to this book and felt tears at the end. Once again I learned about a whole new aspect of the scope of WWII Nazi Germany’s infiltration throughout the world. I had no idea that from 1939-1941, famous Jewish scientists fled from Nazi invaders to Turkey! Turkey had declared themselves neutral, however they were torn and coerced by both Nazi Germany and allied forces to side with them. Many scientists fled and were employed by the University of Istanbul. <br />Maximilian Wagner, a famous scientist, was not Jewish but his sweet wife Nadia was. He left first for Turkey and she was to follow but got picked up and taken to Dachau. Max was able, with his connections and liaison Priest in Istanbul, to have Nadia freed. He gets her a ticket on a so called luxury liner to come to Turkey. The ship’s name Struma.<br /><br />Book begins in 2001 with Maya writing about the visit of Max to Istanbul. (Max, now a Harvard professor, returning to Istanbul to deliver a speech at the University. His guide and University assigned coordinator is Maya).<br /><br />I cannot reveal more. Let me say that book moves back and forth from 2001 to 1939 era to Max’s return visit earlier in 2001. It transitions smoothly, offers much history of Turkey and Romania, as well as WWII horrors such as the ship Struma. It is based on factual history of events.<br /><br />This novel is well written and I highly recommend.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15424814040368952885" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
