  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3464843013?book_show_action=true">Jul 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marge Congress" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marge Congress" href="/user/show/34628-marge-congress">Marge Congress</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/48928025-serenade-for-nadia">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/34628-marge-congress?shelf=2020">2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3464843013" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7375591147420237270">I read this in conjunction with Midnight at the Pera Palace, which made it even more interesting. Maya is Turkish and leads a pretty simple life. She is asked to escort a visiting professor from Harvard when he visits her Turkish University. This becomes a mysterious situation as he used to teach at that University and has come back to re-visit his memories of his life in Turkey. Along with some pieces of history that sometimes verge on &quot;who cares&quot; to the reader, the descriptions of Istanbul fro</span>
  <span id="freeText7375591147420237270" style="display:none">I read this in conjunction with Midnight at the Pera Palace, which made it even more interesting. Maya is Turkish and leads a pretty simple life. She is asked to escort a visiting professor from Harvard when he visits her Turkish University. This becomes a mysterious situation as he used to teach at that University and has come back to re-visit his memories of his life in Turkey. Along with some pieces of history that sometimes verge on "who cares" to the reader, the descriptions of Istanbul from the 30s to the present is quite interesting. We are pulled along with the mystery, which grows as the novel moves on.<br /><br />Mostly the translation works, but occasionally I felt a bit lost. The story is something not known by most people, regarding Jewish professors who were allowed to leave Nazi Germany to teach in Turkey. Sometimes sinister, sometimes lovely, I liked the book as a whole.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7375591147420237270" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


